-- 1. [Problem Restatement] Prove that for all positive real numbers x, y, z, 9/(x + y + z) ≤ 2/(x + y) + 2/(y + z) + 2/(z + x). 2. [Key Idea] Apply the Engel (Titu’s) form of Cauchy–Schwarz, or equivalently the AM–HM inequality, to the three numbers (x + y), (y + z), (z + x). 3. [Proof] Method 1 – Engel (Titu’s) inequality (1) Σ 1/(x + y) = 1/(x + y) + 1/(y + z) + 1/(z + x). (2) By Engel: Σ 1/(x + y) = Σ 1²/(x + y) ≥ (1+1+1)² / Σ(x + y) = 9 / [2(x + y + z)]. (3) Multiply (2) by 2: 2 Σ 1/(x + y) ≥ 9 / (x + y + z). Method 2 – AM–HM inequality (1) Let a₁ = x + y, a₂ = y + z, a₃ = z + x (all positive). (2) Harmonic mean H = 3 / Σ 1/aᵢ, Arithmetic mean A = Σ aᵢ / 3 = 2(x + y + z)/3. (3) Since H ≤ A: 3 / Σ 1/aᵢ ≤ 2(x + y + z)/3 ⇒ Σ 1/aᵢ ≥ 9 / [2(x + y + z)]. (4) Multiply by 2: 2 Σ 1/aᵢ ≥ 9 / (x + y + z). In both methods the desired inequality 9/(x + y + z) ≤ 2/(x + y) + 2/(y + z) + 2/(z + x) is obtained. 4. [Conclusion] Hence, for every positive x, y, z, the stated inequality holds.
